typedef __attribute__
 

Detailed Description

This section defines the data structures used by the driver to provide hardware information, modification and dynamic operation of the driver. These data structures are defined in the header file of the core driver and utilized by the API.

Typedef Documentation

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbbusInterval) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Called on bus interval event only if any isochronous endpoint used.

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbConnect) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Callback called on connection to host event. To check speed at which device has connected to host read speed flag of CUSBD object

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbDescMissing) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, uint8_t epAddr)

Called when descriptor missing event received

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbDisconnect) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Callback called on disconnect from host event. All queued transfer on all active endpoints are completed by driver with CDN_ECANCELED status.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpDisable) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, CUSBD_Ep *ep)

Disable Endpoint. Functions unconfigures hardware endpoint. Endpoint will not respond to any host packets. This function should be called within SET_CONFIGURATION(configNum = 0) request context or on disconnect event. All queued requests on endpoint are completed with CDN_ECANCELED status.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpEnable) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, CUSBD_Ep *ep, const uint8_t *desc)

Enable Endpoint. This function should be called within SET_CONFIGURATION(configNum > 0) request context. It configures required hardware controller endpoint with parameters given in desc.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpFifoFlush) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, const CUSBD_Ep *ep)

Flush hardware endpoint FIFO.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpFifoStatus) (const CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, const CUSBD_Ep *ep)

Returns number of bytes in hardware endpoint FIFO. Function useful in application where exact number of data bytes is required. In some situation software higher layers must be aware of number of data bytes issued but not transfered by hardware because of aborted transfers, for example on disconnect event.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpSetHalt) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, const CUSBD_Ep *ep, uint8_t value)

Set halt or clear halt state on endpoint. When setting halt, device will respond with STALL packet to each host packet. When clearing halt, endpoint returns to normal operating.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbEpSetWedge) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, const CUSBD_Ep *ep)

Set halt on endpoint. Function sets endpoint to permanent halt state. State can not be changed even with epSetHalt(pD, ep, 0) function. Endpoint returns automatically to its normal state on disconnect event.

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbReqComplete) (CUSBD_Ep *ep, CUSBD_Req *req)

Reports request complete callback. Params: ep - endpoint associated with the request req - request which has been completed Note that request received in completion routine may be used again

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbReqDequeue) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, CUSBD_Ep *ep, CUSBD_Req *req)

Dequeues IN/OUT transfer request from an endpoint. Function completes all queued request with CDN_ECANCELED status.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbReqQueue) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, const CUSBD_Ep *ep, CUSBD_Req *req)

Submits IN/OUT transfer request to an endpoint.

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbResume) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Called when device returns from suspend state.

typedef uint32_t(* CUSBD_CbSetup) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD, CH9_UsbSetup *ctrl)

Callback called on setup request received event Params: ctrl contains usb setup request in little endian order

typedef void(* CUSBD_CbUSB2PhySoftReset) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Called to perform soft reset of USB 2 PHY

typedef void(* CUSBD_CdSuspend) (CUSBD_PrivateData *pD)

Called when device controller goes into suspend state.

Function Documentation

struct CH9_UsbSetup_s __attribute__ ( (packed)  )

This structure describes the USB configuration descriptor as defined in USB 2.0 specification section 9.6.3. This structure also applies to the USB other speed configuration descriptor defined in section 9.6.4.

The length of this descriptor in bytes. All configuration descriptors are 9 bytes long.

The type of the descriptor. For a configuration descriptor, this will be USB_DTYPE_CONFIGURATION (2).

The total length of data returned for this configuration. This includes the combined length of all descriptors (configuration, interface, endpoint and class- or vendor-specific) returned for this configuration.

The number of interface supported by this configuration.

The length of this descriptor in bytes. All endpoint descriptors are 7 bytes long.

The type of the descriptor. For an endpoint descriptor, this will be USB_DTYPE_ENDPOINT (5).

The address of the endpoint. This field contains the endpoint number ORed with flag USB_EP_DESC_OUT or USB_EP_DESC_IN to indicate the endpoint direction.

The endpoint transfer type, USB_EP_ATTR_CONTROL, USB_EP_ATTR_ISOC, USB_EP_ATTR_BULK or USB_EP_ATTR_INT and, if isochronous, additional flags indicating usage type and synchronization method.

The maximum packet size this endpoint is capable of sending or receiving when this configuration is selected. For high speed isochronous or interrupt endpoints, bits 11 and 12 are used to pass additional information.

The polling interval for data transfers expressed in frames or micro frames depending upon the operating speed.
